{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T19:09:47.158042+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-22T16:23:10.869256+00:00", "id": 19669702, "conceptrecid": "19669701", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669702", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669701", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19669702", "metadata": {"title": "Global warming tugs at trophic interactions", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669702", "publication_date": "2009", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Climate change impacts are becoming increasingly evident as 1\u00a0\u00b0C warming above pre\u2010industrial temperatures is approached. One of the signature biological effects is a shift towards earlier\u2010timed reproduction. If individual species lack sufficient adaptive plasticity to alter phenology, they will have reduced fitness in a hotter world. Yet, a long\u2010term study of an oak\u2013caterpillar\u2013songbird\u2013sparrowhawk food web reveals that what could matter as much is if trophic interactions are disrupted. Multiple selective pressures may be triggered by climate change, leading to a tug\u2010of\u2010war between the need to stay in synchrony with the timing of maximum food, and the benefits of minimizing predation.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Brook, Barry W.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/b2aed92e26d9f154e0f662359d10c4af", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/5c8d87cf18ee2cced1657299b3fb5ccfa4444b086efa12e10007ec42ba2bf83d", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/99EIAGQJ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/99EIAGQJ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/7a4f22cf2568db6762b7a7693c916eab